      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the classic \"wait, what?\" moment! I can see the goblin logic in your head right now, but let's stick to the real physics. The \"magic\" coin analogy is just a shortcut to avoid getting bogged down in the math, but you're right to want the plain English version.\n\nHere is the deal: **Classical correlation** is like two twins who both love ice cream. If you see one eating a cone, you know the other probably does too, but they made that choice independently. They could have decided to like ice cream yesterday, and their choices don't depend on each other in real-time.\n\n**Quantum entanglement** is different because the particles don't have a definite state until you measure them. It's like two goblins who are so deeply connected that if you ask the goblin on Mars what color his hat is, he hasn't decided yet. But the moment you ask him, he instantly knows what color the goblin on Earth is wearing, even though the goblin on Earth hasn't looked at his hat yet. They are sharing a single \"wave\" of possibilities.\n\nIn classical physics, you can explain this by saying the particles carried hidden instructions (",
